"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847008","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-01","<p>The Government recognises that better provision of defibrillators and increasing the number of people trained in cardiopulmonary resuscitation could help save more lives of those who have a cardiac arrest outside a hospital setting. We therefore encourage organisations to consider purchasing a defibrillator as part of their first-aid equipment, particularly for places where there are high concentrations of people.</p><p> </p><p>The Government does not believe that a regulatory approach is the best solution for this issue. In order to further support the National Health Service and local communities, the Government has provided £2 million to make public access defibrillators more widely available and to increase the numbers of people trained in cardiopulmonary resuscitation.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-03-01T14:42:48.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847008/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847008/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847008/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-22","Defibrillators: Public Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of introducing regulations requiring all public buildings to have access to a defibrillator.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","129182"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847009","Home Office","false","2018-02-27","<p>The Home Office collects and publishes information on the number of police officers on certified long-term sick absence as at 31st March each year. Long-term absence due to sickness includes officers on leave for 28 days or more.</p><p>These data are published in the annual ‘Police workforce’ statistical bulletin, available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales</a></p><p>However, these data do not include the reason for the sick absence.</p><p>The Home Office also collects information on the number of police officers on short/medium term sick absence as at 31st March each year. Short/medium term absence due to sickness includes officers on leave for 28 days or less. Again, these data do not include the reason for the sick absence.</p><p>This information is published by Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary and Fire and Rescue Services (HMICFRS) in their Value for Money profiles, available here: <a href="https://www.justiceinspectorates.gov.uk/hmic/our-work/value-for-money-inspections/value-for-money-profiles" target="_blank">https://www.justiceinspectorates.gov.uk/hmic/our-work/value-for-money-inspections/value-for-money-profiles</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2018-02-27T17:48:04.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847009/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847009/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847009/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-22","Police: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many police officers are on on sick leave due to mental health problems.","false","Biography information for Laura Pidcock","North West Durham","Laura Pidcock","129183"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847010","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-01","<p>The Government recognises that better provision of defibrillators and increasing the number of people trained in cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) could help save more lives of those who have a cardiac arrest outside a hospital setting. We therefore encourage organisations to consider purchasing a defibrillator as part of their first-aid equipment, particularly for places where there are high concentrations of people.</p><p> </p><p>The Department published the Cardiovascular Disease (CVD) Outcomes Strategy in 2013, which highlighted the importance of CPR and availability of Public Access Defibrillators.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has advised that, since the publication of the Strategy, the Community Resuscitation Steering Group (CRSG) has taken steps to address issues relating to CVD outcomes.</p><p> </p><p>These steps include:</p><p>- HM Treasury allocated two tranches of £1 million each to purchasing more Public Access Defibrillators (PADs) and the British Heart Foundation (BHF) has supervised its distribution; and</p><p>- UK Resuscitation Council, BHF, and Arrhythmia Alliance have all undertaken campaigns to increase awareness of CPR and availability of PADs.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-03-01T14:40:20.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847010/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847010/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847010/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-22","Heart Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what plans his Department has to improve the survival rates of out of hospital cardiac arrests; and what role automatic external defibrillators will play in those plans.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","129184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847011","Home Office","false","2018-03-12","<p>The Government has not undertaken an assessment of the effect of rural crime on farmers in the North East or North West Durham. However, the 2015 Commercial Victimisation Survey found that 24 per cent of agriculture, forestry and fishing premises in England and Wales had experienced at least one incident of crime (excluding online crime) which represented a statistically significant fall of six percentage points compared with the 2013 Survey. Vandalism, theft and burglary were the most common crime types experienced by this sector.</p><p>On average there were 330 incidents of online crime per 1,000 premises in this sector, which is around a third of the incidence rate for ‘traditional’ crimes against this sector. The majority of online crime incidents involved computer viruses.</p><p>Findings from the 2017 Commercial Victimisation Survey will be published later this year and this will include more up-to-date findings.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2018-03-12T18:29:14.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847011/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847011/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847011/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-22","Crime: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of rural crime on farmers in (a) the North East and (b) North West Durham.","false","Biography information for Laura Pidcock","North West Durham","Laura Pidcock","129185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847012","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-27","<p>We are currently carrying out further analysis of this issue with a number of housing providers, to investigate and understand the true level of rent arrears for their tenants, what is causing them and any impacts Universal Credit may be having. It will be published when completed.</p><p> </p><p>We also know that arrears are usually temporary and the majority of claimants do succeed in paying their rent, managing their monthly payments and clearing their arrears over time. In our published research available at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/481865/universal-credit-extended-gateway-evaluation.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/481865/universal-credit-extended-gateway-evaluation.pdf</a>, the proportion of Universal Credit claimants who were in arrears at the start of their claim fell by a third after four months. To note, the relevant section is Page 33, Table 3.5. This report is from 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Lastly, research carried out by the National Federation of ALMOs shows over three quarters of their tenants come onto Universal Credit with pre-existing rent arrears. This research can be accessed at <a href="http://www.almos.org.uk/include/getDoc.php?did=7944&amp;fid=9326" target="_blank">http://www.almos.org.uk/include/getDoc.php?did=7944&amp;fid=9326</a>. To note, the relevant section is page 10, section 3.</p><p> </p><p><em></em></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-02-27T16:59:03.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847012/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847012/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847012/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-22","Universal Credit: Rents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent assessment she has made of the effect of universal credit on the number of people in rent arrears in (a) the UK, (b) the North East and (c) North West Durham.","false","Biography information for Laura Pidcock","North West Durham","Laura Pidcock","129186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847013","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-01","<p>The Department collects information on the cost of renting in the English Housing Survey. In 2015-16, the latest period for which figures are available, the average weekly cost of renting a property in the private rented sector for those aged 16-34 was £190 per week and the average rent in the social rented sector for those aged 16-34 was £101. The Department does not publish estimates for those aged under 25.</p><p>These figures can be found in the 2015-16 English Housing Survey housing costs and affordability report: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/english-housing-survey-2015-to-2016-housing-costs-and-affordability" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/english-housing-survey-2015-to-2016-housing-costs-and-affordability</a></p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2018-03-01T15:44:01.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847013/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847013/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/847013/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-22","Rented Housing: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the average cost of renting a property for people under the age of 25 in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Laura Pidcock","North West Durham","Laura Pidcock","129187"
