"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846131","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-01","<p>The table below captures the value of all Confiscation orders granted under the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 since its imposition. The data is based on the ‘current’ order amount which is the amount ordered by the court following any appeals or variations.</p><p> </p><p>The sum of total payments relates to the total amounts paid on those orders since they were imposed, not the total amounts paid on confiscation orders within that year. Similar data is published but is not limited to confiscation orders only made under the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002.</p><p> </p><p>As high value orders are often complex and may involve hidden and overseas assets they can take many years to successfully enforce against, potentially utilising Receiverships or reciprocal enforcement arrangements with overseas authorities. The percentage collected is therefore higher in older orders because there has been more time to enforce.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the time to pay period set by the court may not yet have expired for orders made in 2017 and 2018.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Sum of Current Order Amount</p></td><td><p>Sum of Total Payments</p></td><td><p>Percentage collected</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2002</p></td><td><p>£39,316.53</p></td><td><p>£39,316.53</p></td><td><p>100%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2003</p></td><td><p>£815, 711.15</p></td><td><p>£759,170.67</p></td><td><p>93%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2004</p></td><td><p>£11,716,088.83</p></td><td><p>£10,062,884.63</p></td><td><p>86%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2005</p></td><td><p>£32,718,307.77</p></td><td><p>£28,155,729.15</p></td><td><p>86%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2006</p></td><td><p>£51,164,744.09</p></td><td><p>£41,609,372.30</p></td><td><p>81%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2007</p></td><td><p>£118,084,388.63</p></td><td><p>£61,526,211.27</p></td><td><p>52%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2008</p></td><td><p>£113,180,575.48</p></td><td><p>£69,691,897.81</p></td><td><p>62%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2009</p></td><td><p>£113,055,870.95</p></td><td><p>£79,632,578.28</p></td><td><p>70%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>£152,844,581.76</p></td><td><p>£98,631,957.40</p></td><td><p>65%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>£150,322,850.53</p></td><td><p>£110,043,365.42</p></td><td><p>73%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>£229,119,613.65</p></td><td><p>£124,091,196.22</p></td><td><p>54%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>£203,710,073.01</p></td><td><p>£138,692,216.94</p></td><td><p>68%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>£212,026,970.34</p></td><td><p>£135,069,555.85</p></td><td><p>64%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>£189,051,477.20</p></td><td><p>£112,693,117.51</p></td><td><p>60%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>£388,409,324.42</p></td><td><p>£120,415,398.54</p></td><td><p>31%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>£193,427,145.85</p></td><td><p>£84,801,787.88</p></td><td><p>44%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018</p></td><td><p>£60,244,529.31</p></td><td><p>£1,910,101.99</p></td><td><p>3%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Grand Total</p></td><td><p>£2,219,115,858.35</p></td><td><p>£1,217,825,858.39</p></td><td><p>55%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-03-01T17:57:58.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846131/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846131/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846131/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-21","Proceeds of Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much money was ordered to be confiscated under the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 in each year since its enactment; and what proportion was collected in each of those years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","128827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846133","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-01","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Information about the volumes and outcomes of appeals to the First-tier Tribunal (Social Security and Child Support) is published at: www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics.</p><p> </p><p>The latest statistics can be viewed at: www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunals-and-gender-recognition-certificate-statistics-quarterly-july-to-september-2017.</p><p> </p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-03-01T17:58:19.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846133/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846133/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846133/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-21","Disability Living Allowance: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people have won an appeal against the withdrawal of their disability living allowance at a tribunal in the latest period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","128828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846134","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-12","<p>In August 2016 there were 645 people equivalent to 572.5 on an FTE basis working within SSCS, and in Nov 2017 we had 595 people equivalent to 527.7 FTE. It is important to stress that these figures were taken as a snapshot and may have been different during other periods in both years.</p><p>Information before 2016 is not held centrally and can only be obtained at a disproportionate cost.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-03-12T15:32:29.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846134/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846134/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846134/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-21","Social Security and Child Support Tribunal: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff were employed in Social Security and Child Support Tribunals in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","128829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846135","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-02","<p>I refer the honourable member to the answer given to PQ 125513 on 9 February 2018 regarding the cost of running Gov Facility Services Limited.</p><p>The estimated value including subcontractor costs is not yet determined. The MoJ will work with GFSL to ensure that subcontractors provide value for money and effective delivery of service.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-03-02T14:57:18.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846135/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846135/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846135/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-21","Gov Facility Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 9 February 2018 to Question 125513, on Gov Facility Services, what the estimated cost is of running Gov Facility Services Limited, including sub-contractor costs, in each year from 2018 to 2022.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","128830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846136","Ministry of Justice","true","2018-03-01","<p>Prison officers do a challenging and vital job to help protect the public and we are committed to making sure we have enough staff to deliver safe regimes in our prisons.</p><p> </p><p>Detached duty is one of the sensible and proportionate measures we take to cover resourcing pressures and ensure we run safe and decent regimes in prisons as well as being able to respond appropriately to any operational issues that arise.</p><p> </p><p>In 2016 the former Secretary of State announced HMPPS would be recruiting an additional 2,500 prison officers by December 2018. Good progress is being made to hit this target, with 1,970 additional officers recruited by 31<sup>st</sup> December 2017. These new staff will reduce the need for Detached Duty.</p><p> </p><p>When there is a need to accommodate staff in hotels, we work hard to ensure the best possible value for money for the taxpayer and have controls in place to help keep costs to a minimum.</p><p> </p><p>Where possible, bookings are for specifically timed trains and always in standard class to help keep costs to a minimum.</p><p> </p><p>We are able to provide data on hotels and rail bookings made through Redfern Travel Ltd <strong>only</strong>.</p><p> </p><p>Please see table attached for data from 2013 – 2017.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-03-01T17:36:01.063Z","2018-03-05T19:13:23.033Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846136/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846136/answer","Table  PQ 128831-128837.press cleared (002).xlsx","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846136/answer","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846136/answer/previousversion/44279","Biography information for Rory Stewart","54","Justice","Justice","2018-02-21","Prison Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much money was spent from the public purse on (a) hotels and (b) other expenses for prison officers on detached duty in each month from January to June 2016.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","128831"
