"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846159","Home Office","false","2018-02-27","<p>The Proceeds of Crime Act provides the statutory scheme for the recovery of criminal proceeds; its purpose is not to recover stolen goods for victims. There are other legislative powers to support victims to recover stolen goods or receive compensation, including the Powers of Criminal Courts (Sentencing) Act 2000. However, assets recovered using Proceeds of Crime Act powers can be used to compensate victims when a compensation order has been made by the court following a conviction. The annual Asset Recovery Statistical Bulletin records the amount of the proceeds of crime paid in compensation to victims: £36 million in 2016/17.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2018-02-27T15:58:14.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846159/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/846159/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-21","Crime: Victims","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effectiveness of the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 in supporting victims of crime to recover their stolen goods.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","128851"
